column312: We are finding it very frustrating to find funding. We are based in Europe and helping in Europe but most funding, even European funding, is for people doing our work in global majority countries and the US. When there is funding, the competition is FIERCE. And much funding is given by orgs that do not take unsolicited applications so it feels like funding is based on who you know and not what you do. We've also been a part of a few participatory grant making processes and found them to be hugely time consuming and also in some ways unfair. For instance, we were asked to review grants from orgs in different countries and different sectors to ours. We took hours to educate ourselves on the local contexts of those groups - but know not every group partaking in the process would have the same capacity or drive to do this

column312: It's extremely difficult to get funding in the SWANA region, especially as an arts and culture organization not working on healthcare/humanitarian aid, particularly as the political landscape of the region gets more volatile. Additionally, many funders have their own political agendas (especially bilateral agencies that we have since learned to avoid), as the renewed international interest in the Israel-Palestine conflict has really influenced our relationship with funders who do not take a hard stance against genocide. Some have even censored our work (we have since stopped working with those donors), and we've rejected funds from prospective funders because we know better now and we will not compromise on our politics. This shuts us off from a huge amount of funding. We've also had bad experiences with the administrative & programmatic cost of projects vastly outweighing the support offered by the fund, which has really strained our team's efforts. and we had to apply for more funding just to cover salaries. Lastly, the civil society space in lebanon is extremely small and we have close contact with organizations that do receive lots of funding (over $1 million budgets), so we are keenly aware of where the money actually is! The majority of these “feminist” organizations are anti-trans and anti-sex work whose work on LGBTQIA+ is quite narrow and focused on visibility and asking for acceptance from society.

column311: Running the Community and Media Platform
column312: TMWT is a independent media platform and community centring the diverse perspectives of Muslim women. This project was started as a passion project in November 2020 with just three of us on the team. We have personally funded everything from our pockets since then, and we’ve had to pause operations because the running costs are increasing and we still haven’t gotten access to funding. We did apply for grants at intervals, but we haven’t been fortunate enough to get one. We’re looking at a paid membership model for community members and sales of merchandise to keep it afloat for now.

column289: Financiamiento flexible e institucional para la sostenibilidad de organizaciones de base feminista
column311: Sostenibilidad institucional, autocuidado, planificación colaborativa y estratégica, fortalecer investigación y generar cambios en políticas públicas según demandas juveniles.
column312: • La mayoría de las organizaciones de base no tienen una nómina, debido a fondos limitados a proyectos o a corto plazo. Tampoco hay oportunidades para capacitación técnica o financiamiento para el desarrollo de planes institucionales que permitan fortalecer el trabajo y el alcance.  • Cuando no hay un fondo central, se reproduce el trabajo no remunerado que históricamente afecta a las mujeres. Este trabajo no remunerado se transfiere de la esfera "privada" a la "comunitaria" y es "romantizado" por las agencias donantes, en lugar de ser reconocido económicamente. El activismo, la organización comunitaria y la lucha por nuestros derechos es un trabajo histórico que ha recaído en las mujeres. Estas dinámicas continúan precarizándonos.  • Se debe reconocer la diferencia en los costos de trabajar con adultos y menores. Trabajar con menores en situaciones vulnerables es más costoso porque se deben seguir muchos protocolos de seguridad, además de cubrir necesidades básicas. A veces, los donantes planifican proyectos dirigidos a menores con una idea preconcebida de trabajar con adultos. O estos costos solo se reconocen al trabajar con ONG internacionales, y no al trabajar con organizaciones de base, reproduciendo así un sistema de discriminación basado en infraestructura.  • Se debe reconocer la experiencia y el conocimiento de las organizaciones de base. La percepción del conocimiento debe ser decolonizada y no solo entendida como algo que se obtiene de la academia. No debe haber una relación condescendiente o jerárquica con nuestro trabajo, que es fundamental y clave. Cuando las grandes organizaciones se van de nuestras comunidades, somos nosotras quienes permanecemos y sostenemos el tejido comunitario.  • Todas las plataformas de financiamiento deben tener accesibilidad lingüística.  • Debe haber oportunidades de financiamiento dirigidas exclusivamente a organizaciones de base lideradas por mujeres.  • Deben existir tres tipos de fondos: Fondos centrales - enfocados en el fortalecimiento institucional (para cubrir monitoreo, comunicaciones y participación en espacios clave); Fondos a corto plazo para financiar actividades, y fondos a largo plazo para financiar proyectos (al menos dos años de implementación).  • Otras formas de apoyar a las organizaciones de base lideradas por mujeres incluyen visibilizar nuestro trabajo, conectarnos con otras oportunidades de financiamiento, capacitar a nuestro equipo y crear oportunidades de networking.

column312: Para AzMina, sustentabilidade vai muito além de obtenção de recursos, mas práticas de governança, cuidado, compartilhamento e aprimoramento de conhecimentos. Financiamentos institucionais, não condicionados a projetos, são fundamentais para investirmos no planejamento da nossa área operacional e financeira, em estratégias de captação de recursos mais condizentes com a maturidade da nossa organização e com estratégias e metodologias de monitoramento e avaliação em nossas formas de trabalho e projetos. O crescimento da equipe e da estrutura da organização nos últimos quatro anos é prova irrefutável da sua competência nesse quesito. Em 2024, pela primeira vez em nossa história, estamos com uma meta de prospecção de 2 milhões de reais (cenário ideal) ou R$ 1 milhão de reais (cenário real). Com isso, toda a equipe, está especialmente envolvida em relacionamento com financiadores, viagens, abertura de novas frentes de diálogo e formatação de muitos projetos de maior impacto, em parcerias com outras organizações. Tem sido um ano desafiador, mas sem dúvidas crucial para sairmos do modelo de projetos isolados e nos dedicarmos a ações estruturantes e mobilizadas por redes com o intuito de promover impacto sistêmico.

column312: We have chance funding from NED, PRLM, FFM, JPF, BR, FGHR and Kumudra. But, PRLM, FFM and JPF will end soon.The security situation in Myanmar continues to deteriorate, with armed clashes taking place in many parts of the country. In 2024, fighting has progressively intensified particularly in Kachin State, Myanmar. Conflict, involving the deployment of heavy weapons, aerial bombardment and shooting, including in urban and populated areas, has driven a surge in displacement, civilian casualties, protection risks, and humanitarian needs. Given the scale and intensity of the unfolding crisis, affected women and girls have inter-connected, multi-dimensional needs that require a comprehensive multi-sectoral response to address survival needs and promote dignity and greater resilience. More than 3 million people are internally displaced across Myanmar, with the vast majority – more than 2.7 million – forced from their homes by conflict and insecurity since the 2021 military takeover. In Kachin State, two third of the population become internally displaced people, most of them are women and girl including most vulnerable women and girls they are pregnant mothers, breast feeding mothers, disables’ mother/wife, disable mothers, single women headed mothers have more than 3 children under 9 years. Since October 2023, the rapid spread of fighting across large swathes of the Myanmar country has propelled a drastic increase in displacement, exacerbating pre-existing needs and raising grave protection concerns. Compounding this situation is the coming monsoon season (expected between June and October) which threatens to exacerbate already dire humanitarian gender needs and vulnerabilities in many areas where displacement is highest. Against this backdrop, a timely injection of support from the HTOI Gender organization is needed to assist those recently displaced, many of whom are yet to receive any assistance due to significant underfunding and who will soon be exposed during the monsoon season. In line with the overarching strategy and priorities of the 2024 humanitarian gender needs and response plan, this allocation should provide to deliver lifesaving humanitarian assistance and services in areas with the highest levels of new or repeated displacement, prioritizing townships with the most severe needs.

column312: Nuestra experiencia es que hemos sido capaces como mujeres indígenas YUKPA, discriminadas, con muchas limitaciones de conocimiento, de organizarnos, fortalecer capacidades, generar acciones de incidencia a nivel nacional e internacional para el reconocimiento de nuestros derechos como mujeres y la justicia de género, diagnosticar necesidades, generar acciones y buenas practicas para la atención diferenciada de nuestra población comunitaria indigena con perspectiva de género, que responde al principio de localización (Grand Bargain), rindiendo cuentas y presentando proyecto con muy pocos recursos, que hemos tenido que asumir desafios para incorporarnos a la Arquitectura Humanitaria en nuestro país, para acercar la Respuesta Humanitaria a nuestro territorio y a nuestra población, estigmatizada en muchos casos por las instituciones que deben garantizar los servicios y derechos, para el fortalecimiento del  triple nexo. Con muy poco, hemos avanzado y hecho mucho más que otras organizaciones con más estructura, recursos y sobretodo  manteniendo nuestra independencia y autonomía. Hemos hecho realidad el principio El Tejido Fortalece, pues creemos, valoramos y afianzamos los vínculos con otras organizaciones nacionales e internacionales a traves del reconocimiento, respeto y la comunicación como valores fundamentales de nosotras y hacia afuera. Y ahora estamos enfocadas en crear nuestra Red Comunitaria de Protección de Mujeres Indígenas YUKPA desde el enfoque de desarrollo, paz y respuesta integral y multisectorial a las necesidades, de manera culturalmente apropiada. Con énfasis en la prevención y mitigación de la Violencia de Género

column312: Our experience with funding has often been challenging as donors typically prioritize what they perceive as urgent needs without consulting us, the front-line responders who understand the ground realities best. This disconnect is particularly evident in responding to the impacts of climate change in Iraq, where women and girls are disproportionately affected. Despite our significant efforts to raise international awareness and attract attention to this critical issue, securing the necessary funding to support these vulnerable populations remains an uphill battle. We urge funders to engage more closely with local organizations and consider our insights to ensure that resources are allocated effectively and equitably.

column311: Global Media Monitoring Project (GMMP)-2025 and staff recruiting
column312: Global Media Monitoring Project (GMMP)-2025 is first undertaken in 1995, captured baseline data on crucial gender equality indicators in the news media. The next edition of the project planned for 2025 will gather insights on the state of play 30 years later, contributing evidence to the status of the implementation of Section J of the Beijing Platform for Action three decades since its adoption. Specific Objectives  The specific objectives of the 2025 GMMP are as follows:  i.	To build capacity of civil society groups engaged in women’s rights or gender equality work, media professionals, students and others to carry out participatory media monitoring with a gender lens. ii.	To update the data on the status of gender equality in the news media 30 years after Beijing, expanding the time series dataset commenced in 1995. To collect baseline data from countries for which data have not been gathered. So far, the GMMP dataset spans 163 countries with data points across a 25-year period, and with at least one observation for each variable and country.  iii.	To gather new data on the global top priority concerns of the day. News topics identified for special attention are: a.	Climate change  b.	Women politicians and political aspirants c.	Gender-based violence d.	Peace, security and conflict iv.	To gather insights on how Technology-Facilitated Gender-Based Violence (TFGBV) plays out on news platforms through a monitoring of user feedback and comments beneath news stories published online. v.	To draw lessons for the news media industry on the opportunities that a gender, diversity and inclusion orientation presents to navigate the current crises and to build long-term viability. To develop specific, actionable recommendations and a basket of levers of progress towards gender equality in the news industry.

column311: To empower women and women with disabilities.
column312: My experiences are very long but I want to tell them to you in short.My name is Neetu and I am from India. I am a handicapped woman. I struggled a lot in my childhood due to my disability. I could not study. I always stayed at home and could never go out and I was also abused.And my rights were also violated. I struggled a lot due to disability. I have a lot of experiences, but I cannot talk about all of them, but today I am moving forward with all those experiences and doing social work. I do not have any funding from anywhere for women and disabled women. I am running my organization by somehow collecting some funding from around me. I want to say this much about this research. It is a good platform from where organizations, funding types and good work can be done. Thank you so much for including me in this survey.

column312: Como pequeña organización y de trabajo de base muchas veces se hace dificil hacer atención e incidencia en política pública por falta de recursos económicos y de compañeras que puedan ser contratadas con salarios justos. Creo que ahora los donantes buscan que se hagan las tres áreas de trabajo pero no colaboran con un donativo que sostenga de manera digna el trabajo en cuestión de paga y de sostenimiento en el tiempo. Buscan que las organizaciones seamos sostenibles, sin embargo las actividades que se hacen nunca se cobran pues la gente con quienes trabajamos se encuentran en situaciones de vulnerabilidad. Pocas veces contamos con el tiempo y personal para pensar en actividades que permitan la venta de productos, lo que nos dificulta ese tema. Las agendas cambian constantemente y esto hace que seamos flexibles y resilientes , sin embargo nos quemamos muy rápido. Muchas veces por conseguir los financiamientos nos da miedo preguntar las prioridades en cuanto al número de participantes en los proyectos; ¡se ve bien que hagamos muchos número con poco recurso o será que les interesa que sean pocos beneficiarios con mayor numero de capacidades? Este tipo de incertidumbres suceden mucho, ellos tienen el dinero y muchas veces el poder lo que en ocasiones a las organizaciones nos hace sentir que debemos de responder a sus exigencias. Cotidianamente dejamos lo importante por lo urgente, dejamos de profesionalizarnos, de cuidarnos, de actualizarnos, de ser personas por estar respondiendo a las agendas.   Una cosa importante es que en realidad quienes estamos haciendo el trabajo de base somos quienes estamos en contacto con la verdadera realidad, no con números o estadísticas sino con las vidas; es prioridad atender este tipo de organizaciones frente a la incidencia en política pública. También agradecer quienes están en esos lugares que han elegido dar la lucha desde allí, pero que jamás olviden a quienes la damos en el territorio y no en los escritorios.

column312: As a mid-sized fundraising and programme-delivery organisation, we apply for grants from trusts, foundations and corporations, as well as relying on individual donations. Our most successful long-term funders have formed a relationship with us that transcends funding or application requirements. We are finding it more challenging to have successful applications through traditional channels (ie, find an application, complete it, send it in). We are shifting our focus to being more visible and encouraging funders to approach us. This allows us to run projects with our in-country partners in India, Nepal and Bangladesh. We imagine that the challenge for smaller grassroots organisations is even greater (this is certainly true for our in-country partners when fundraising individually), and recognise the need for more resources to support them access funds.

column289: We urge funders to provide flexible, unrestricted funding to help organizations cover operational costs, invest in capacity building, and pursue long-term advocacy and systemic change.
column311: We would spend the money on covering core operational costs, capacity building for our staff and volunteers, and enhancing our technological infrastructure to better manage and expand our programs.
column312: Our experience with funding has highlighted several critical challenges. While we appreciate the support we've received for specific projects, the lack of unrestricted funding has constrained our ability to cover essential operational costs and invest in long-term capacity building. Additionally, the competitive nature of funding often diverts our focus from impactful advocacy and systemic change efforts to short-term, project-specific goals. We urge funders to recognize the importance of flexible funding that supports not only the direct outcomes but also the sustainability and growth of the organizations driving these initiatives. Investing in core operations, infrastructure, and strategic development is crucial for fostering resilient and effective movements.

column311: Оплата труда 3 сотрудниц, бухгалтерки, регистрация юридического лица и оплата основной деятельности
column312: Наша организация сейчас занимается доступом трансгендерных людей к сулугам здравоохранения. В России с 2023 года полностью запрещен трансгендерный переход. Нам необходимо заниматься регулярными мониторингом, исследованиями положения трансгендерных людей, однако абсолютно всефоны отказывают в проведении исследований. Вторая наша задача - научная деятельность. Не просто абстрактная, а деятельность, направленная на восполнение научной информации о трансгендерных людях, которую преднамеренно учничтожает государство. Однако слово "наука" и "исследование" вызывают алергию у доноров, которые не понимают контекста.  Наша задача, связанная с наукой, - адвокационная, восполняющая недостаток информации для трансгендерных людей, специалистов в области медицины, ВИЧ и т.п. Кроме того, из-за специафики работы с сфере медицины и здравоохранения, мы постоянно находимся на связи с медицинским сообществом, которое не готово слушать активистов, но открыто к коллегам, говорящим на их языке. Этот контекст тоже никому не ясен, но ни один из доноров и не делал попытку узнать подробнее о том, чем мы занимаемся и почему это важно. Понимание мы находим, только если среди представителей доноров есть люди из России или связанные с ней.

column312: Since our creation (2022) we only received funding from FRIDA Feminist Fund and the European Network Against Racism. Until 2024 spring we were unregistered and we had very little opportunities to apply for funding. We applied for several things, but we were continuously rejected. Roma feminists are their agendas are not supported neither in mainstream European or in feminist philantrophic organizations. We need a Roma Feminist Fund which would support initatives with core funding so that the movements can build up and strategize. Without that we will achieve very little, as we are burnt out in working for free and receiving no appreciaton and acknowledgement for our work. Please, take this message forward and reach out to us if you think we can collaborate together in the creating of a Roma Feminist Fund, or if you could support us and other Roma feminist initatives. Thank you!

column312: Peer Review for Grants: Peer review is essential for evaluating research proposals submitted to funding agencies. It ensures rigorous assessment of scientific merit and quality. An exploratory study1 investigated the skills necessary for effective peer reviewers on grant review panels. These skills include critical analysis, communication, and understanding of funding agency priorities. Reviewer experience and the use of technology impact skill development. Whether in-person or virtual, effective peer review requires expertise and attention to detail. Navigating Research Funding: Researchers seeking funding should explore available opportunities. Understanding grant mechanisms, eligibility criteria, and application processes is crucial. A comprehensive guide2 can help you navigate the intricate world of research funding and grants. It covers various aspects, from proposal writing to budgeting. Feedback and Grantsmanship: Grant applicants receive feedback during the review process. Constructive feedback helps improve proposals. Expert reviewers provide margin comments and key recommendations to enhance grantsmanship and compliance3. Reviewer Expertise: Reviewer expertise significantly influences decision-making in peer review. Although peer review is the gold standard for evaluating research, it’s essential to recognize its limitations and continually improve the process.

column311: FDEA will allocate the money to holistic programs, including education, economic empowerment, healthcare services, and advocacy, for adolescent girls and young women with disabilities.
column312: Our experience with funding has shown that while there is growing interest in supporting adolescent girls and young women with disabilities, securing sustained and flexible funding remains a challenge. Short-term grants often limit the scope and impact of our initiatives, and there is a critical need for funders to understand the importance of long-term investments in education, economic empowerment, and health services. We also advocate for a more inclusive funding approach that directly involves the beneficiaries in decision-making processes to ensure that their specific needs and voices are prioritized.

column312: Nosotras hemos tenido solo un financiador durante 30 años. Trabajamos en la región LAC y contamos con un presupuesto de 64.000 dólares al año. Somo un equipo bastante reducido donde la coordinadora de la red tiene un contrato al 50% sin embargo trabaja al 200%, la asistente de la red tiene un contrato del 100% pero no puede abastecer con todo el trabajo; y nuestra compañera que se encarga de administrar las finanzas tiene un contrato al 30%. Somos muy comprometidas con los movimientos de mujeres, mujeres diversas y feministas, sin embargo sentimos que nuestro financiador, en los últimos años, ha hecho que los procesos de solicitud de fondos sean más rigurosos, alejados de la realidad y requieren una inversión de tiempo considerable que resta la dedicación al tiempo y atención que merecen nuestras actividades. Por el financiamiento tampoco podeos hacer muchas actividades que requerirían presencialidad. Colocamos aquí la respuesta 43 Construcción de instrumentos para la incidencia política y social, fortalecimiento de alianzas en el LAC y con otros movimientos del Sur Global, identificación de fondos concursables y canales de financiamiento, e investigación  ¡Gracias AWID!

column312: En contextos de migración y racismo, las colectivas formadas integramente por mujeres en condición de migración son estigmatizadas y no se nos reconoce nuestras capacidades para gestionar fondos. Siempre hay duda sobre si podemos o no ejecutar un proyecto. Y como es un espacio donde se entra en competencia con organizaciones de personas europeas blancas por la obtención de recursos, es más fácil que se nos vea como beneficiarias de los proyectos de estas organizaciones que protagonistas activas en la gestión de nuestros propios proyectos. Las convocatorias a subvenciones son muy burocráticas y llenas de requisitos que a veces no podemos cumplir y siempre con una rigidez que no toma en cuenta la realidad diversa de las mujeres migrantes. El auge de la ultraderecha en Europa está generando un gran desafío para muchas colectivas de mujeres a las cuales se está dejando de financiar por el lobby que hacen estos grups que cada vez más están legitimando su presencia en las instituciones públicas.

column312: We are observing a shift in funding from project calls to public procurement processes. This means that public authorities shift the financial risk for realising their action plans on feminist NGOs. In the past two years, we had two such projects, the first was implemented with some loss (EUR 10 000), the second failed due to too constraining time and budget conditions, leaving us to cover the expended costs and loosing the guarantee we had to pay upfront (about EUR 50 000 in total). While we luckily have some space for action to balance the 2023 budget, this could mean the end for other organisations in our country.

column312: Hemos tenido la oportunidad de formarnos como colectiva a partir de un proyecto financiado por IPPF y administrado por Católicas por el Derecho a Decidir México, sin embargo el proyecto finalizó y nos quedamos sin fondos ya que no los administrabamos nosotras, sin materiales y sin salario. Decidimos continuar por que amamos lo que hacemos, trabajar en comunidades y dar acompañamiento a mujeres y personas con capacidad de gestar que decidan abortar. A partir del 2023 fuimos invitadas por Ipas para una subvención y eso nos permitió hacernos de materiales y medicamentos en donación, lo que ha permitido que podamos continuar brindando acompañamiento, sin embargo éste es gratuito, la mayoría de las compañeras cuentan con un empleo remunerado a excepción de 2 que nos estamos dedicando a buscar fondos y proyectos subvencionados y que a la vez tenemos que compartir este que hacer con la maternidad, lo cual en ocasiones complica el trabajo. Aún con los pesares que en ocasiones nos acogen no desistimos y seguimos en la búsqueda de subvenciones y financiamientos, así como de fortalecimiento y especialización en lo que hacemos.

column312: Before and after the establishment of the Divine Empowerment Microfinance Enterprise for women, as a Finance Director, I have worked with several nonprofits funding for years. I have been always responding to requests for proposals/information and written to the government or foundation grant application, but I have not been able to succeed in all my effort but few, mostly from voluntarily contributions. However, I am currently responsible for everything related to grants – grant research, strategy, scheduling, writing, submissions, making copies, follow-up reports, filing, foundation relations, etc. It is  a daunting prospect to say the least, especially since the Organization is unable to employ a finance assistant. Below is my daily work responsibilities and some I have created over the years for the effective funding utilization of the Organization and in response to communication failures, missing information, and even a missed deadline or two, along with the realization that with a little effort, I could work smarter, not harder! Build Your Own Grants Folder Using a structure that works for me, I built a grant-specific file that I control and fill it with everything needed to maintain a consistent and successful grants program for our organization. Create a regular schedule (quarterly, biannually, or annually) for updating information that tends to change throughout the year, such as program budgets, new employee resumes/duties, outcomes information, etc. These are the main folders I use:  	Grant Applications I separate all in-process and completed grant applications into folders based on funder type (Churches; Civic Groups; Charitable, Corporate, Family, and Community Foundations; Federal, State, and City Government; etc.), and within that, by funder name, and then by year, and kept electronic copies of all documents related to a particular year’s application together. 	Attachments & Appendices Include folders to hold every document that I may think of that might potentially be requested in a grant application. I have folders for everything from tax documents tax-exempt status letters) to marketing materials/brochures, to resumes/bios of key staff. This allows you to easily put your hands on whatever might need to be uploaded to a grant application. 	Planning & Tracking Tools Create a single place to hold information pertaining to all of the applications you’ve submitted for each fiscal year, amounts requested, amounts received, program allocations, grant reporting deadlines, and other information.    	Prospect Research Searching and vetting potential funder prospects is an ongoing task for me. I keep information and contacts I’ve made with potential funders in one place, separated by funding priority, so I have a starting point for researching potential supporters for upcoming projects/programs. 	Program Descriptions & Data/Outcomes One of the most difficult things for me as been trying to quickly familiarize myself with what all of the many programs in two separate organizations did so that I could articulate the need clearly in a grant application. Keeping program brochures, program/project descriptions, and updated outcomes/numbers of clients served in a single location, by program and year made responding to numerous grant applications each month much simpler/quicker. 	Program Needs Information If there’s one thing every grant professional has experienced, it’s program staff tackling you in the hallway to tell you ALL of the things their program needs IMMEDIATELY for which you surely could find a grant, right?? Obviously, all of these requests should be vetted by management or other senior-level staff and in line with the organization’s strategic direction, but once they are, it’s important to keep track of who needs what, when, and how often. Develop & Implement Systems to Track Grant Information When I came in there was no access to a grants management database system, I tried to build my own in Excel and keep it up to date to manage potential funder prospect lists, grants calendar/deadlines, submissions, and tracking/follow-up. Use drop-down menus to gather information so to I can create pivot table reports that I can share with the Board of Directors, senior management team, resource development staff, and stakeholders. The amount of data I can collect and the information you can glean from that data is endless! Here are just a few examples of reports that I found useful: 1. Fiscal Year-to-Date (YTD) Funding Requested/Received/Pending – this information is great for Board and/or senior management who might want to know how much funding could be expected in the coming year or to compare to fundraising goals on an ongoing basis. 2. Total Restricted vs Unrestricted Grant Funding Received Annually – this is good data to have at hand especially when I need to show the worth of grants and grant writing to the powers that be in my organization! 4. All Grant Submission and Grant Report Deadlines by Month – whether I am applying for  more grants per year for my organization, having a calendar showing every deadline I have come up over the next 12 months will be essential for ensuring you never miss one! I also develop and Implement Processes for Determining and Monitoring Program and Organizational Needs  5. Program Level: Program managers are generally intimately familiar with their own program budgets, so they know how much money they have on a monthly basis to spend on each line item. On the other hand, individual staff members are much more knowledgeable about whether those amounts are sufficient to provide quality services. Despite this, staff members are often not encouraged to consider what additional things (supplies, outside professional services, equipment, etc.) might improve the program, the impact of services, or the work environment. • Management Level: While program staff, if asked, could probably spend hours discussing all of the extra "stuff" they would love to have in order to do their jobs, management staff have to approve any requests, and they’re often the ones who have to say "NO" (in big letters). For me, this meant getting quietly accosted in the hallways by program staff asking me to write a grant to get "x" for Project A – only to find out that they didn’t get the idea approved first. • Development Level: In larger organizations like the one I worked at, there can be a number of development staff in different roles other than grants – managing volunteers, individual donors, events, major gifts, in-kind donations, etc. Program level staff would often come to me about a need they thought could be filled by a grant, but was really something more appropriate for an individual or a corporate donor to provide. I had to come up with a way to determine, on an ongoing basis, what each program’s needs were (both annual and one-off needs) and a system for prioritizing them so that I could quickly and accurately match potential grant opportunities with the organization’s various programs and projects. The system I put into place looked like this: 1.	Program Level Discussion – program managers facilitate a program needs discussion during  monthly team meetings; 2.	Request – managers complete a request form explaining the need(s), the expected impact, the cost and the priority level (critical/need it now, need it soon, or nice to have); 3.	Development Staff Review – staff compiles all needs into one list and proposes a method of need fulfillment (grants, in-kind donations, volunteers, individual or corporate donor, etc.); 4.	Senior Management Approval – executive director and accounting staff vet the final list and  provide feedback to development staff; 5.	Feedback Loop – development staff begin the process of fulfilling program needs and regularly  inform programs of the status of their requests. 6.      Monitoring/Updating – lists are updated every six months.  I have to admit that the grants management systems I created as a way to survive my trial-by-fire weren’t always so clear cut, and there was A LOT of training/education on the grants process that had to occur at the management AND program level before things started working more smoothly. That said, the effort was absolutely worth it. It takes time, but ultimately, building and implementing the infrastructure to manage grant information, potential prospects, requests, deadlines, and program needs was the only thing that saved me from being burned to a crisp.

As such, women and children with disabilities have had just little or no experience of what it feels like to be able to get access to a safe space or shelter in terms of gender based violence, war or natural disaster. Our plan to construct this multipurpose shelter over the years has met lots of challenges however to the fact that inclusion is very expensive. However, we cannot be left behind because we are disabled rather, our disability should be the more reason to enjoy safety because disability rights are human rights.

Alors que c'est maintenant que nous avons vraiment besoin deux pour faire avancer les droits des femmes et leur protection. Notre organisation est jeune, mais grande. malheureusement contraintes aux ressources financières pour l'atteinte des objectifs. column312: As  social change makers,  who have worked for human rights organization like IRC, USAID, and community radio stations; who have survived/overcome adversity, understand the problems, already know the local culture, history, language and social context, decided to organize the below organization. The Chandelierd’ Incorporation Personnes Vulnérables (CIPEV) is a local NGO duly registered in the Kissidougou region Guinea Conakry, West Africa since August 17,2020. CIPEV’s mission is centered on advocating for the rights of individuals with the aim of fostering societal and international harmony. We are inspired by  the Convention on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women through its general recommendations 19 (1992), 23 (16th session, 1997) and 35 (2017), and the Beijing Platform for Action (1995). Therefore we are committed to the following:  A.	We highlights the need and  to squarely address the underlying practices, beliefs, attitudes and behaviors across society that perpetuate and tolerate sexual and gender-based violence, and informed by Regional experiences and knowledge and  committed to regionalism .  B.	We aims to specifically   prevent and respond to sexual and gender-based   violence against females in rural areas; contribute to improved knowledge on female in the Mano River Region; monitor and report progress; identify policy options; provide a platform for dialogue; collaborate with  intergovernmental organizations and civil society in the development of our region;  implementation of effective pro-women policies and programs; and promote a common voice for women in the region.

column289: Transparencia en los procesos de selección y adjudicación de propuestas, retroalimentación de observaciones de las propuestas presentadas.
column311: Ejecución de proyectos que beneficien a mujeres que sufren violencia y el ejercicio pleno de sus derechos, para consolidar procesos de trabajo institucional.
column312: a planificación estratégica institucional para el quinquenio 2020 - 2025 de OMAK, ha marcado como una de sus líneas de acción el promover la apropiación, exigibilidad y generación de propuestas de derechos de las mujeres en base a la revalorización de la identidad y practicas culturales. En base a la experiencia y procesos emprendidos, se ha focalizado y dado mayor énfasis al derecho de garantizar a las mujeres una vida libre de violencia, para lo cual durante los últimos años, a partir de la gestion de proyectos apoyados por la cooperación internacional, se ha podido ampliar las posibilidades de acceso a mecanismos integrales de prevención y atencion a mujeres. La integralidad es dada, no solamente por la multidisciplinariedad del equipo técnico, sino tambien por la formación por competencias de mujeres defensoras de derechos como promotoras comunitarias, quienes cumplen con las funciones de sensibilizacion, identificación de casos, orientación, acompañamiento e incidencia.  Por otro lado, se ha potenciado el uso de herramientas digitales para la producción y difusión de mensajes a través de medios de comunicacion tradicionales y alternativos.  Finalmente, se considera que este tipo de trabajo, de contacto directo con mujeres provenientes del área rural y periurbana ha permitido una mejor reflexión y aplicación del enfoque de interseccionalidad, reconociendo las multiples violencias y discriminación a las que las mujeres se encuentran expuestas.

column312: We depend on extrenal fundings for about 90%. We do not have a permanent funder but have recieved funds from UNTF  for periods of upto 3years. This funding enabled us to expand on our work on empowering women and girls and increased school enrollement for indigenous girls who are highly disadvantaged in education by their own parents and the community at large. The core funds helped us build our Institutional capacity and gave us visibility both in our work as well as a feminist organozation. We created 5 community tailoring workshops which have trained about 200 girls. Our staff recieved monthly salaries and someallowances to carter for their wellbeing. The project which was very successful helped us developped our capacity to implement, report, carry out evaluation etc. The funding ended in 2022. We have some small fundings from INGOS which are helping us sustain our Organization and also work in communities. They are flexible and easier. Application and reporting are simplified. We have institutional support of 50% from one of the fundings which is 25000USD yearly, and that permits us to sustain our work and institution. We support 3 women groups in bio-agriculture with the rest of the 50% each year. For the research we need it to delve deeper into sustainable resourcing of funds for feminist movement  who are taking so much risk to raise the voices of women.

column312: Over the years, our experience with funding has been marked by both opportunities and challenges. While generous support has enabled significant progress in areas like capacity building, institution development, and advancing queer women's rights, securing consistent and long-term funding remains a challenge. The unpredictability of funding cycles and shifting donor priorities often require adaptability and resilience. Additionally, external factors such as the economic impact of the COVID-19 pandemic and legislative changes like Uganda's Anti-Homosexuality Act 2023 have significantly influenced funding dynamics and necessitated strategic adjustments. It is crucial for funders to recognize the importance of sustained support and flexibility to address evolving needs and unforeseen challenges in the pursuit of human rights and gender equality.

column312: Relevant Experiences:  Community correspondents’ networks  Community correspondents’ network was established in 2013, in Greater Khartoum and during last seven years in along different Sudan’s states, so as to contribute to the limited media coverage in deserted population areas via:  •	Engaging with the local communities to acknowledge the role of the media in enhancing the transparency and accountability in basic and strategic services and facilities. •	Providing a platform for the community correspondents to communicate their communities’ issues and concerns with different media outlets; •	Engaging with local media channels that trying to give voice to the masses of people whose voices are not heard.  Media for local governance: linking up citizens with local governance structures: “Media for local governance issues” known as Kolan Liltanmia Project (KLP) is part of Alag’ projected funded by the British Council, during 2016-2018, the project has twin targets:  1) cultivate on the capacity of journalists and CCs for better report on local issues in Gezira stat;  2)advocate for better engagement of citizens in local policy making structures. The development of networks of community correspondents and their training were based on Alag’s greater Khartoum experiences. The ultimate goal of KLP is to develop new techniques for covering and reporting on local governance issues with the aim of better citizen-state engagement. Alag have worked with a range of local partners including state radios, community radios, local print media, and the peoples’ committees through whom the project has uniquely succeeded to link local authorities with citizens.    Specific Expertise to media:   Capacity building program for journalists (broadcast &print): The capacity program includes training, internship and exchange visits with different media institutes and outlets, at national and regional levels, themes of training workshops  •	Journalism skills; •	International Human Rights (i.e. international instruments, addressing claims, •	 Conventions) •	UN security council Resolution 3125; •	Basics of Gender concepts and terms; •	Good governance issues, (with concentration of Participatory and public budget issues);  •	Digital & personal security. Building partnership with Omdurman National Radio: In collaborations with Fredric Ebert Foundation Alag Centre has led a distinguished initiative on mainstream gender principles within the Omdurman Radio’s programs. Two consultative seminars have been conducted including Alag founders, heads of social programs department and representatives from the ministry of social welfare- (Women Directorate). The seminars were followed by forums that have been attended by numbers of heads of department including political affairs and Albeit Alsudani. Memorandum of understanding (MOU) has been signed between Alag Centre, Omdurman Radio and the Ministry of Social Welfare, in accordance with (MOU) Alag has conducted: -	series of gender brainstorming sessions and seminars for the Radio program producers, decision makers, drama writers and some of journalists working with different social program; -	Quick review for selected radio program, (i.e. talk shows, women, youth, and peace program) so as to evaluate and analyze the programs’ contents from gender perspectives, (in terms language, time of broadcasting and consultations with other actors…).    Protection mechanism project for women journalists (provision of Safe Environment); The project targets, journalists, CCs and Women Human Rights Defenders (W/HRDs), that use media to promote the rights of vulnerable women and girls. The projects provide financial and technical support to women journalists and W/HRDs towards safeguard of the rights, safety, autonomy and dignity. Sexual and Gender-Based Violence (SGBV) was set as a priority by many of our partners and beneficiaries. It was agreed that media had a very important role to play in curbing SGBV via providing necessary space.

column312: Na minha experiência pessoal, percebo que há pouca oferta de patrocínio de sustentabilidade, os patrocínios focam em realização de projetos mas só garantem o financiamento da implantação do projeto e não da sua continuidade, e a busca por financiamento para 'sustentabilidade' de projetos depende da sustentabilidade da organização conseguir manter o projeto enquanto faz captação, e sem a garantia de recursos não é possível investir no projeto o que muitas vezes impede um projeto de crescer. Diferente das oganizações que buscam sustentabilidade autônoma na venda de serviços ou publicidade, nossa organização está focada em fazer projetos de forma gratuita, visando alcançar nosso público-alvo que são mulheres, pessoas LGBTQIAPN+, feministas, ativistas, defensoras de direitos humanos, entre outras minorias que foram socioeconomicamente excluído dos desenvolvimentos das tecnologias digitais, portanto não buscamos sustentabilidade na cobrança de serviços, pois seria um contracenso e distanciaria ainda mais o nosso público-alvo das discussões em torno das tecnologias.

column312: Most of the funders to not facilitate the Caribbean Transmasc community in anyway. While we support feminist group, it would be disrespectful to consider us a feminist group because not everyone in our community aligns with that. There has been no funding that helps Caribbean transmen/transmasc community navigate their lives in such a homophoic/transphobic country. No HRT support for us, no asylum, no actually therapist who cares, no surgery, no access to gender affiming products, no housing, no food, just nothing at all for us because of the limitations of these funders and their grants. There is a whole other set of persons in the community that needs help, and while I know we can't help them all, the progress that in community work in countries like USA, CA, UK, EU is not the same progress in the Caribbean, Africa and other small countries. We are also deserving of support and it will take a lot of work to make the Transmasc community in Jamaica want to be visible because of how behind we are with making them feel inclusive. Then funders want to make remarks like "they wont continue to fund if we aren't getting the numbers". If we were focusing on the this community in this region then it wouldn't take long to get the numbers and it is unfair that you are so easy to give up all in the name of business? I don't like it to be honest but I cant change it. It's up to you all.

column312: I feel very strongly that donor organisations need to acknowledge that their grant applications haemorrhage our resources. Every time we get through to a 2nd round application, and then get turned down, we have spent the equivalent of our Executive Director's salary for two months in the resources that go into doing a proper, well researched application. And shorter (one page applcations) are not better - they still need the same budgeting, scoping, etc of a full proposal, but this time you have to put the energy into distilling it so every word sings.  Honestly? Donors should either put people aside who can worl with us on our applications, or pay us for our time and energy in submitting proposals they've turned down. And the way nobody provides feedback on why a propsal was turned down is iniquitous.

column312: Las mujeres y lesbianas tenemos un doble desafio financiero al intentar proyectos autónomos , dado que ya somos marginadas de los sistemas laborales/economicos tradicionales y la autonomia por su parte es un ejercicio de constante equilibrio entre la sostenibilidad y la precarización, ya que requiere de mucho trabajo no pagado. Nosotras hemos volcado nuestra vida a construir un proyecto politico activista de terapia situada feminista y espacios culturales lesbicos , amamos lo que hacemos, nos proyectamos por mucho tiempo más, pero es muy dificil sostenernos económicamente y requerimos de mayor apoyo, ya que consideramos que nuestra labor es fundamental e histórica para las lesbianas y mujeres.

column312: Es necesario que las financiadoras confíen más en las capacidades de las organizaciones, que los procesos para recibir financiamiento y los informes sean accesibles y amigables, así como el poder brindar mayores recursos. En muchas ocasiones solicitan administración de recursos previos muy altos, pero si no confían en nuestras capacidades y no nos dan financiamiento ¿Cómo vamos a lograr alcanzar algún día este requisito? Por otro lado, pensamos muy importante que, cuando se trabaja interna y externamente con grupos en situación de vulnerabilidad, como nosotras con mujeres con discapacidad, los presupuestos deben ser flexibles y altos, debido a que los gastos siempre se elevan debido a los ajustes razonables necesarios para realizar adecuadamente los proyectos y todos los elementos como herramientas y material que se tiene que generar específicamente para ello. Es mucho trabajo operacional y de recursos invertido que las financiadoras no consideran.

column312: Our experience with funding has highlighted several critical challenges, including the volatility of donor priorities, which often shift in response to global events and crises, making it difficult to sustain long-term programs. Additionally, stringent reporting requirements and a lack of flexibility in fund allocation often limit our ability to adapt to the evolving needs of the communities we serve. We believe that funders should consider a more holistic approach to supporting organizations, focusing on building capacity and resilience in the long term. This would allow us to address not only immediate concerns but also to invest in sustainable development and systemic change. Ultimately, a more collaborative relationship between funders and organizations, based on trust and mutual goals, would significantly enhance our collective impact.

column312: Last year, alongside my work at Empowering Practices, I was involved in narrative change initiatives within a smaller CSO. Despite our significant potential, we had to scale back due to limited funding. Meanwhile, a larger organization in Turkey received substantial funding, which wasn’t primarily directed towards narrative change. This situation highlights a dilemma: while it’s important to support established organizations, concentrating funding on one entity in a region can skew power dynamics, especially when that organization is asked to collaborate with others. Larger organizations, having easier access to funds, can sometimes become gatekeepers, which complicates equitable collaboration. I believe that when a donor funds an organization and expects it to form alliances, there should be clear guidelines on how resources are to be shared. This would discourage larger organizations from withholding resources from those with potential. It is especially a responsibility of feminist funders.

column289: Las mujeres negras importa
column311: Justicia de género
column312: Estimado equipo de AWID,  Nuestra experiencia ha sido nula. Muchas gracias por su interés en conocer más sobre nuestra labor. En la Corporación Club de Lectura Mariposas de Amor, nos dedicamos a promover la justicia de género y los derechos de las mujeres en Buenaventura, Colombia. Nuestro trabajo se centra en apoyar a mujeres afrocolombianas, especialmente madres cabeza de hogar que han sido víctimas de violencia de género, y en empoderar a niñas y jóvenes vulnerables para que se conviertan en líderes de cambio en sus comunidades.  Nos alineamos estrechamente con los valores y objetivos de AWID, y estamos interesados en explorar oportunidades de colaboración para fortalecer y expandir nuestros esfuerzos conjuntos en estas áreas fundamentales.  Agradecemos su consideración y esperamos poder trabajar juntos para avanzar en la justicia de género y los derechos de las mujeres.

column289: Nous notons l'absence de certains bailleurs en Afrique de l'ouest francophone. Notre région est peu desservie par les bailleurs, fondations et ONGI.
column311: Nous organiserons de meilleures conditions de travail avec les ressources techniques, matérielles et humaines nécessaires en faveur des droits des filles et des femmes.
column312: Au niveau de l'IPBF nous avons pu observer le faible intérêt des bailleurs fonds pour notre région; le Burkina Faso étant un pays enclavé et pauvre, la plupart du temps, peu de bailleurs connaissent notre existence. Notre travail n'est pas reconnu et nous avons du mal à intéresser les bailleurs de fonds. Nous avons remarqué également que la langue constitue une barrière qui limite notre accès à certains bailleurs. Aussi, peu de bailleurs de fonds intervienne dans notre région. Un aspect également important demeure le défis des ressources humaines qualifiées, de nos compétences internes à rédiger des projets de qualité; mais surtout notre faible connaissance de la majorité des bailleurs internationaux. Au niveau national, les grandes ONGI préfèrent travailler avec des organisations identifiées et changent ou intègrent rarement de nouvelles organisations. La langue aussi constitue une grande difficulté dans la mobilisation des ressources, la plupart des bailleurs de fonds étant anglophones.

column312: CBRN-TL's experience with funding has been marked by challenges in securing consistent, long-term support, which is essential for the sustainability of programs empowering persons with disabilities. While short-term grants have enabled project-specific achievements, the lack of sustained funding often hampers the organization’s ability to plan for and invest in broader systemic changes. Flexibility in funding, coupled with a deeper understanding from donors about the complex needs of the communities CBRN-TL serves, is crucial for creating lasting impact.

column312: Cudecoop es una organización gremial de representación de defensa del movimiento cooperativo en Uruguay. La forma de dar respuesta a las necesidades de las cooperativas generalmente mediante la presentación de proyectos a fuentes de financiamiento. En los temas de género, venimos trabajando hace más de 15 años en diagnóstico, formación, autonomía económica, liderazgo, redes. Detectamos las necesidades de las mujeres cooperativistas o grupos precooperativos y luego buscamos fondos que puedan apoyar la demanda. Hemos presentado proyectos a Unión Europea, otros invitados por organizaciones feministas locales (como Fondo mujeres del Sur), a Inefop (Instituto de formación profesional). Pero luego de finalizado los plazos, es dificil mantener las acciones.

column312: Je suis actuellement Président de notre Association pour la Défense des Personnes Vulnérables. J’ai eu l’opportunité de travailler sur quelques projets, notamment la campagne de sensibilisation des femmes maltraitées , la journée culturelle et la formation, où j’ai géré des subventions et des dons dans les autres associations. Cette expérience m’a permis de développer des compétences en rédaction de propositions, de gestion budgétaire et de présentation de rapport final. Un défi majeur a été de naviguer dans les exigences variées des bailleurs de fonds, ce qui m’a appris l’importance d’une communication claire et transparente. Je pense qu’il est essentiel de renforcer les collaborations entre les organisations internationales pour maximiser l’impact des financements.

column312: Actualmente nuestra organización atraviesa una crisis financiera, lo que generó que compañeras queden sin trabajo y otras sobrevivan apenas con proyectos puntuales. Chile no es prioridad para ningún fondo grande ni fondo feminista (ni siquiera para AWID), porque es un país de buen producto interno bruto; pero este índice falla en reconocer las desigualdades y centralismo del país. A esto se suma las dificultades de conseguir financiamiento nacional tras el Caso Convenios (caso de corrupción de algunas ONGs que llevó a que se cerraran múltiples fondos nacionales y que se sobre-burocratizaran otros). Estamos en un contexto de desesperación, agotadas de usar nuestro tiempo libre para postular y cansadas de encontrarnos con fondos de embajadas con condiciones imposibles (exigiendo que hayamos ejecutado fondos de más de 500.000 dólares y obligando a presentar proyectos con otras cuatro organizaciones o más). En general, estamos agotadas: para algunos fondo somos "privilegiadas" y no necesitamos ayuda y para los otros, manejamos muy poco dinero y no nos vemos estables en el tiempo. Ya conocemos organizaciones amigas que han tenido que han tenido que congelar su funcionamiento y tememos ser las siguientes. A esto se suma que las mismas entidades del gobierno de Chile nos piden trabajo gratis, al mismo tiempo que fallan en generar fondos concursables dignos y que no nos precaricen.

column312: My experience with funding has been a mix of challenges and learning opportunities. Securing funding, particularly for initiatives focused on Itgnc asylum seekers and refugees, has often been difficult due to the limited availability of grants that cater specifically to these groups. Additionally, the application processes can be complex and time-consuming, which is especially challenging for smaller organizations like ours that may not have dedicated grant writers or administrative support.  On the positive side, the funding we've managed to secure has had a significant impact on our ability to provide critical services, such as shelter, food distribution, and safety training for ITGNC individuals. This has not only allowed us to expand our reach but also to create a more sustainable support system for our beneficiaries.  However, one of the main issues I've encountered is the inflexibility of some funding options. Often, the grants come with very specific guidelines on how the funds can be used, which sometimes doesn't align with the urgent and unpredictable needs of the community we serve. I believe that more flexible funding options, coupled with more accessible and straightforward application processes, would greatly enhance our ability to meet the needs of our community effectively.  Overall, funding is the lifeblood of our work, and while it comes with its challenges, it also presents opportunities for growth and impact. My hope is that this research can contribute to making the funding landscape more inclusive and supportive of organizations working with marginalized communities.

Otro de los ejes que tenemos es compartir información sobre las rutas migrantes en México por medio de la obra de teatro NorteHada. column311: Leadership development for Dalit women and strengthening our organizational capacity.
column312: Our experience with funding has often been shaped by a lack of consistent, flexible support that truly addresses the long-term needs of Dalit women’s movements. Many funders tend to prioritize short-term projects over sustainable change, leaving us grappling with financial uncertainty and limiting our ability to build lasting impact. Additionally, we have observed a tendency to overlook the specific intersectional challenges Dalit women face, with many donors grouping caste-based struggles under broader categories, which dilutes the unique urgency of our work. What we need are funders who not only provide resources but also trust Dalit women to lead their own movements, allowing us the space to define our own strategies and narratives.

column289: As Dalit Disabled women, our intersectional struggles are recognized and resourced.
column311: Building the leadership and agency of Dalit disabled women by investing in capacity-building programs, advocacy initiatives, and creating platforms that amplify our voices.
column312: As a Dalit women disabled group, our experience with funding has often been one of exclusion and invisibility. Funding mechanisms rarely acknowledge the intersection of caste, gender, and disability, leading to our needs being marginalized or overlooked in broader feminist and disability rights agendas. Resources are often allocated to well-established, upper-caste women-led disability groups, leaving us, as Dalit women, underfunded and unable to access the support we need to create meaningful change.
